{{Infobox U.S. legislation|name=Honest Ads Act|fullname=|acronym=|nickname=|enacted by=|effective date=|cite public law=|cite statutes at large=|public law url=|acts amended=|sections created=|sections amended=|leghisturl=|introducedin=Senate|introducedbill=|introducedby=[[Mark Warner]], [[Amy Klobuchar]], [[John McCain]]|introduceddate=|title amended=}}The '''Honest Ads Act''' ([https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/senate-bill/1989 S. 1989]) is a bill in the [[United States Senate]] legislative body to promote regulation of campaign advertisements online by online companies such as [[Facebook]] and [[Google]]. The act is a bipartisan bill sponsored by Senators [[Amy Klobuchar|Amy Klobuchar (D)]], [[Mark Warner|Mark Warner (D)]], and [[John McCain|John McCain (R)]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/10/19/558847414/what-you-need-to-know-about-the-honest-ads-act|title=What You Need To Know About The Honest Ads Act|work=NPR.org|access-date=2017-11-09|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/united-states/21730652-they-could-eventually-receive-kind-scrutiny-banks-received-after-financial|title=America’s tech giants have no political party to protect them|work=The Economist|access-date=2017-11-09|language=en}}</ref> The bill was proposed on October 19, 2017, as a response to investigation regarding Russia purchasing political ads during the [[United States presidential election, 2016|United States 2016 presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/honest-ads-act-facebook-google-twitter-russia-2017-10|title=Senators have a new plan to fix a major loophole that let Russia take advantage of Facebook and tech giants|work=Business Insider|access-date=2017-11-09|language=en}}</ref> There is also a companion version to this bill in the House of Representatives, HR 4077, sponsored by Representative [[Derek Kilmer]].{{cn|date=August 2018}}
== Legislative background and content ==
Political ads on television, news print and on the radio are all currently required to disclose who has paid for the advertisement under the [[Federal Election Campaign Act|Federal Election Campaign Act of 1971]], but this is not a requirement online. The bill would amend the 1971 law to make "reasonable efforts" to ensure ads are not purchased "directly or indirectly" by foreign countries. The legislation would require companies to disclose how advertisements were targeted as well as how much the ads cost.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/mccain-honest-ads-act-for-digital-transparency-belies-2008-campaign-2017-10|title=John McCain is backing a digital transparency bill that probably would've gotten his 2008 campaign in trouble|work=Business Insider|access-date=2017-11-09|language=en}}</ref>
== Reaction == Companies such as Google have argued against regulation as being too restrictive, in favor instead for self-regulation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-24/lobby-group-for-facebook-google-to-pitch-self-regulation-of-ads|title=Lobbying Group for Facebook and Google to Pitch Self-Regulation of Ads|date=2017-10-24|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-11-09}}</ref>
